[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The objectives, structure and defining features of the United Nations 
[normal]Partnership on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities (UNPRPD) as potential partner for UK’s work on disability and development.
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Perspectives of persons with disabilities on disability and development in the context of discussions on the post-2015 develop
[normal]ment agenda documented through the work of the UNPRPD and its participating organizations.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Given its focus on partnership-building, knowledge creation and value for money, and taking into account its [bold]potential for fostering UN system-wide coherence in the promotion of disability rights as well as its on-going close collaboration with civil society and organizations of persons with disabilities, the UNPRPD represents a natural partner for UK’s work on d[bold]isability and development.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A number of principles will have to be taken into account in order to fully integrate disability into development[bold] in the context of the post-2015 development agenda[bold]. These include among others: the disability-disaggregation of c[bold]ritical socio-economic data; the application of accessibility standards to the physical environment, transportation, information and communication infrastructure; and the realization of the principle of meaningful involvement of persons with disabilities -[bold] [bold]“Nothing about us without us”.[bold]The United Nations Partnership on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities[bold]Overview
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
